You&#39;ve got several options. The easiest would of course to just use a `Queue`, Java&#39;s got some implementations for you ([arrayblocking][1], [concurrentlinked][2]). You could overwrite any of them to add a shift method:

    public E shift(E newElement) {
        E old = take();
        put(newElement);
        return old;
    }

To make this threadsafe, you&#39;ll need some synchronization.

If, for some reason, you prefer other collections, that&#39;s possible, too. Mind that these might not be thread safe. I would not use an ArrayList, because of rather bad complexities, but a LinkedList should be fine. Overwriting it would need this shift:

    public E shift(E newElement) {
        E old = getFirst();
        addLast(newElement);
        return old;
    }

As long as you use only the shift method, you can be sure of the fixed size. If you want to force it, you&#39;ll have to overwrite more methods, of use a delegator.

